      <hedline>
        <hl1>For Affordable H.M.O.'s</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Margaret W Leung letter on Sept 18 article calls for government action to make health insurance affordable</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With unprecedented rises in premiums (''Frustration Grows With the Cost of Health Insurance,'' front page, Sept. 18), coverage under health maintenance organizations has become a luxury for those who can afford it.</p>
        <p>A free market ideally fosters competition so that consumers benefit from better quality at reduced prices.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With unprecedented rises in premiums (''Frustration Grows With the Cost of Health Insurance,'' front page, Sept. 18), coverage under health maintenance organizations has become a luxury for those who can afford it.</p>
        <p>A free market ideally fosters competition so that consumers benefit from better quality at reduced prices.</p>
        <p>However, this doesn't appear to be the case in the health care industry.  If the country isn't ready for universal coverage, the government should at least work with the industry to ensure consistent and affordable coverage.</p>
        <p>Private H.M.O.'s should continue to exist so that consumers can choose plans that best fit their needs.  But the government must make sure that there are adequate services at prices families can reasonably afford.</p>
        <p>MARGARET W. LEUNG  Berkeley, Calif., Sept. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
